       Alternate Application ROMs for the WebTV Plus Internet Receiver

                                Jack Palevich

                            WebTV Networks, Inc.

                             WebTV Confidential

                                   Draft 1

Introduction

With the Client 2.2 release, the WebTV Plus Internet receiver has the
ability to run any number of alternate application ROMs. These ROMs are
downloaded from the WebTV Service and installed on the WebTV Plus hard disk.
When the user requests the application, the application is quickly loaded
from the hard disk. When the user is finished using the application, the
regular WebTV applicationĀ is restored.

Alternate application ROMs are ideal for offline games and other
applications (like word processors) that cannot easily be implemented as
web-based applications.

Features and Limitations

Alternate Application ROMs have these benefits:

   * They have full access to the WebTV Plus Internet receiver's hardware
     and software, including the RAM, the graphics and the hard disk.
   * They can be written in any combination of HTML, JavaScript, C, C++, or
     MIPS assembly language.
   * The application can have up to about 1Mb of code. (But note that MIPS
     code is not as compact as x86 code. MIPS code is roughly twice as bulky
     as x86 code.)
   * The application can use about 2.5Mb of RAM.
   * Potentially any feature of the WebTV software can be replaced,
     extended, or modified to support the needs of the application.

The limitations are:

   * Because each application is implemented as its own ROM image, the
     application's minimum size is 4Mb. (Fortunately, application ROMs
     compress fairly well, because they contain lots of machine language
     instructions.)Ā It takes about 20 minutes to download an application.
   * Developing an application requires that the developer have access to
     the WebTV Client source code.
   * Applications can only be installed via the WebTV service. It is not
     possible for a third-party to sell their application ROMs directly to a
     WebTV customer.
   * Because the box reboots when an application launches, the application
     runs off-line. This has the following effects:
        o The application does not have access to the network.
        o Because there is no log-on, the application does not know which
          user is using it.
   * All polling behavior is suspended while the application runs. (Polling
     resumes automatically when the application terminates.) This includes:
        o TV reminders
        o TV recordings
        o Data Download
        o EPG (TV listings) download
        o MessageWatch
   * In order to provide space for the application to run, the TV experience
     is disabled while the application runs.
   * Should WebTV ever switch to a new operating system, the alternate
     application ROMs would have to be recompiled.
   * Should WebTV ever switch to a different kind of hardware, the alternate
     application ROMs would have to be recompiled.

While these are fairly strict limitations, the technique is powerful enough
for:

   * Off-line games like Doom and You Don't Know Jack.
   * Off-line applications, such as word processors.

Developing Alternate Application ROMs

Alternate application ROMs are developed the same way that the WebTV Client
application rom is. Alternate application ROMs can therefore take advantage
of all of the documentation, tools, and knowledge that has been developed at
WebTV for creating the WebTV Client application rom. The general approach is
to develop using the native platform tools and a WebTV Plus simulator. Once
the application is working, the same source code can be compiled to produce
an application rom which is downloaded into a WebTV Plus box for testing.

The following development environments can be used:

   * Macintosh PowerPC with 32Mb of RAM, 1Gb of disk and CodeWarrior.
     (Simulator only.)
   * Solaris unix. (Simulator and ROM compiling.)
   * Linux with 64Mb of RAM, 2Gb of disk, gnu tools, (All features
     supported.)
   * Windows 95/98/NT with 96Mb of RAM, 4Gb of disk, Visual C++ 5.0, gnu
     tools. (All features supported.)

To develop your application ROM:

   * Verify that you can build the regular application ROM.
   * Pick a unique C preprocessor symbol for your application.
   * Create a subdirectory for your application source files.
   * Add your source files to the subdirectory.
   * Add your source files to the project. (This is done differently on each
     platform.)
   * Make sure that your source files are not compiled as part of the
     regular client.
   * In order to provide enough ROM space for your application, undefine
     parts of the application ROM. To get an idea of what can be removed,
     open the file client/Makefile.defines and search for the word DOOM.
   * Compile your code and debug it, as much as possible, using the
     simulator.
   * Create an application ROM and debug it using the regular tools (squirt,
     par, etc.) for your platform.

UI Guidelines for Alternate Application ROMs

Alternate Application ROMs should adhere to the following UI guidelines:

   * Unlike the main Client ROM, alternate application ROMs should not have
     a power-off state. They should launch into their UI immediately upon
     launching, rather than waiting for the user to press the Power button.
   * If the user presses the Power button, the aarom should quit, and reboot
     back into the main application ROM. It is OK to ask the user if they
     want to save their state.
   * As much as possible, adhere to the standard WebTV UI guidelines.

Making your application ROM available for installation on WebTV boxes.

Once you have your application ROM ready to distribute to end-users, you
will need to solve several problems:

   * Inform the user that the application is available.
   * Allow the user to request the application.
   * Deliver the application to the user.
   * Allow the user to run the application.

The solution to each of these problems is domain-specific, and beyond the
scope of this document. Check out the You Don't Know Jack Engineering
Specification for a solution that's correct for games.

The Boota Client Function

The boota client function has been added to the Client 2.2 release to enable
the creation and running of alternate applications. This client function has
the following syntax:

     To create an approm the syntax is:
     clientfunction:boota?partition=partition&offset=offset&action=create&size=size&source=source.

     To run an approm the syntax is:
     clientfunction:boota?partition=partition&offset=offset&args=args&size=size&source=source.
     Running an approm tries to be robust: If the partition does not
     exist, or if it does not contain the correct information, it is
     created on the fly. This makes the action=create version of the
     boota client function somewhat redundant. However, the
     action=create version is still useful, because it forces the
     approm to be written, whether or not it appears to be valid.

        Parameter     [used by run or create] Description
        partition     [both] Names the alternate appROM 's boot
                      partition. Required.
        offset        [both] Offset in bytes from the start of the
                      alternate appROM's boot partition to the
                      code. Defaults to 0. Use this to store more
                      than one app rom in the same boot partition.
                      Since there is a limited number of top-level
                      partitions (about 30), this may be useful to
                      allow a large number of application ROMs to
                      be installed at the same time. Optional.
        args          [run] Argument string to be passed to the
                      alternate appROM. Optional.
        action        [create] Used to indicate which function to
                      perform. If the parameter is present, its
                      value must be 'create'. If this parameter is
                      present, and the value is 'create', then the
                      client function will install the alternate
                      application ROM. If the parameter is missing,
                      then the client function is going launch an
                      already-installed application ROM. Required
                      for create.
        size          [both] Size of the partition to create, in
                      bytes. This value will be rounded down to the
                      nearest megabyte. If the partition already
                      exists, and it is too small, it will be
                      deleted, and a new larger partition will be
                      created. Required.
        source        [both] The URL of the approm.o image to
                      install. This must be a file://Disk/ URL.
                      Required.
        onfail        [run] The URL to go to if the approm cannot
                      be run. This must be a file:://Disk/ URL.
                      Optional.

Typically the boota?action=create client function is called at the end of a
group download.

Typically the normal boota client function is called from the HREF of a
link, or the target of a button. See the offline games pages for examples.

If any of the parameters are are invalid, the boota client function goes to
the onfail URL, if one is supplied. (For debug builds of the client a
diagnostic message is printed out to the debug console.)

Appendix A: WebTV Plus features for Game Developers

The following features are available for game development:

   * The complete source for the WebTV port of the game Doom.
   * For normal games, there is a 512 x 384 x 8-bit-per-pixel
     double-buffered graphics mode.
   * For more adventurous developers, there is a 2D sprite engine with
     hardware rotation and scaling, and 16 bits-per-pixel YUYV graphics.
   * The IR keyboard can have any 4 keys down at once, and has both key down
     and key up events.
   * The audio hardware and software allows real-time 16-bit, 44-kHz, stereo
     mixing.
   * VFAT file system. (30Mb of read/write disk space available.)
   * Game logs and crash logs allow valuable information to be collected
     from beta-testers and end-users.

